label chapter8:

    # [Scene: North Pier | Dusk]

    scene bg ch7_453e40_1 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Gulls wheel; a winch groans somewhere offstage; an old diesel coughs then settles]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Urgent strings, rising under the dialogue]

    "You stand ankle-deep in the kind of dusk that makes everything look like memory—salty air clinging to your jacket, the field notebook heavy against your hip. Aiden is beside you, head bent over the spread of paper and phone-light, his breath fogging in the cold. He folds a corner of a schematic to make room for a list of terms" "maintenance fund,' 'staged access,' 'main-lane clearance."
    show aiden_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    aiden_reyes "If we put the living shorelines out here,' (he taps a strip on the map) 'it'll slow erosion without corralling boats. We leave the main channel—what's left of it—clear for the trawls. Mateo's lane stays. You're thinking Spartina and eelgrass, not concrete."
    "You reach out, fingers brushing a salt-stiffened ribbon. The co-op's banners—patchwork squares sewn by hands you know—snap like small flags of insistence. The plan in front of you is both fragile and stubborn, like seaweed caught on a rock."
    show maya_kwon at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_kwon "Exactly. Living shorelines where they don't intersect gear lanes. Floating platforms where they do. And metrics—Priya's right—we have to say exactly what success looks like in numbers and timelines."
    show priya_anand at center:
        zoom 0.7

    priya_anand "Three measurable outcomes minimum. Sediment accretion rates, percent eelgrass survival at six months, and community labor hours logged. Fund disbursement conditional on those metrics. Secure, transparent, auditable."
    "You hear the practical click of her words align with the ragged music of the pier. It feels good—businesslike and honest—until you look up and see Old Man Reyes watching from his cane, his mouth folded into the map of all the storms he's survived."

    "Mateo Reyes" "We used to pull nets through this mud and laugh about the fish that wouldn't leave us alone. After the '29 storm we took rifle covers and tea to the neighbors. You youngsters think plans live on paper. They live on hands."
    "His cane taps the wood. The cadence of his memory becomes the rhythm of your proposal; his salvaging stories start turning into clauses in your head—mutual aid language, shared maintenance days, a rota for platform use."

    aiden_reyes "We can put a clause for shared gear access. No exclusive structures, clear signage, rotary scheduling. That way holdouts won't feel like they're losing their lanes."
    "A woman from the co-op—her hands callused, her jaw set—runs a hand over the banner where a child's embroidery reads 'Seabreak.' She looks at the map, then at the water, then back to you."

    "Fisher" "Promise me the platforms won't trap the nets when the tide runs fast. Promise me we won't hand our grounds to some glossy plan that forgets who fishes here."
    "You feel the room—this creaking, wind-battered room under open sky—leaning on your shoulders. You hear the hunger for both promise and proof in the question."

    maya_kwon "We won't promise anything we can't measure. We'll pilot a strip—eelgrass here, floating platform there. If it tangles nets, we iterate. If it doesn't hold sediment, we—' (you meet her eyes) '—we change it. This is a living plan for living people."
    hide aiden_reyes
    hide maya_kwon
    hide priya_anand

    scene bg ch7_453e40_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A soft digital ping as she scrolls through projections]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A taut pulse underlines her presence]
    show dr_elara_voss at left:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_elara_voss "Erosion projections show a 12–14 Percentage increase in scarping at the northern promontory if storms intensify at the modeled rate. Living shorelines slow accretion, yes, but their load-bearing is limited under surge. The platforms will need anchoring that accounts for dynamic stress."
    show aiden_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    aiden_reyes "Then we engineer the anchors. Not a wall—just smart tie-offs and floating access. Nobody's handing the town to concrete."
    "Dr. Elara Voss studies him, then—briefly, like a fault line easing—smiles at his brazen charm."

    dr_elara_voss "You talk like someone who keeps a thermos at the ready. Fine. If the anchors are engineered and the timeline includes maintenance checks after storm events, I'll annotate the projections to reflect that."
    show maya_kwon at center:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_kwon "That—' (you swallow) '—that helps. Priya, can you structure the funding so the engineering review is a requirement before phase two?"
    hide dr_elara_voss
    show priya_anand at left:
        zoom 0.7

    priya_anand "Conditional funding with staged release. First disbursement for pilot setup, second for verified six-month metrics, third for platform anchoring if—and only if—the data supports expansion."

    menu:
        "Tie a scrap of new fabric to the banner":
            "You knot a bright square to the banner—an oath and a signal. Someone nearby murmurs 'good luck,' and the patch flaps like new resolve."
        "Fold the banner and set it aside":
            "You fold the banner carefully, smoothing old creases. The action feels cautious, like keeping a promise safe until it's earned. Aiden watches you, appreciating the quiet ritual."

    # --- merge ---
    "The pier begins to feel like a small, shaking body of work—something you can steady."
    "The pier begins to feel like a small, shaking body of work—something you can steady. People jockey for small wins. A young fisher claps a hand on Old Man Reyes' shoulder, another checks his phone for"
    "tide times and shares them with the group. Conversation accelerates in a dozen small threads."
    hide aiden_reyes
    hide maya_kwon
    hide priya_anand

    scene bg ch7_453e40_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: People talking over one another, but it's the productive buzz of a community finding its rhythm]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Pulled-up tempo; staccato strings]
    show councilor_tomas_hale at left:
        zoom 0.7

    councilor_tomas_hale "Splendid turnout. Important work. But look—the region needs assurance. A visible, headline-friendly seawall sends a message to investors and insurers. It says: Seabreak Hollow is defended."
    "The words hang like a gauntlet. Some heads nod—insurance and investors are real, and funds can move the town fast. Others tighten. You can feel the temptation: a seawall would be immediate, photogenic, and politically saleable."
    show aiden_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    aiden_reyes "A seawall cuts the marsh off. It robs us of the very buffer that gives us fish later. It's a short-term headline that costs us long-term harvest."

    councilor_tomas_hale "And so you'd gamble with people's roofs and paychecks for... what—marsh grass? Poetry? We need assurance, not fiddling with plants."
    "A low, hot sound has been building—the sound of people weighing fear against hope. A few fishers look toward the channel; others watch Hale, calculating a future where insurers write checks only for walls."
    show maya_kwon at center:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_kwon "It's not poetry. It's infrastructure that breathes. It's cheaper in maintenance than repairs after a failed wall. And it's work for people here—volunteer days, paid maintenance, local stewardship that keeps skills alive."

    "Mateo Reyes" "When we repaired nets after the big one, we didn't get a check for a wall. We got neighbors and sweat. That kept us more than a single barrier ever could."
    "Dr. Elara Voss steps forward, tablet in hand, her steel gray eyes narrowed but not unkind."
    hide councilor_tomas_hale
    show dr_elara_voss at left:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_elara_voss "A hybrid approach is viable. A strategically placed, low-profile defense at critical chokepoints coupled with living shorelines elsewhere could meet insurance criteria while preserving marsh function. But it demands monitoring, adaptive management, and—again—measured outcomes."
    hide aiden_reyes
    show priya_anand at right:
        zoom 0.7

    priya_anand "Which is exactly what the grants require."
    hide maya_kwon
    show councilor_tomas_hale at center:
        zoom 0.7

    councilor_tomas_hale "That sounds complicated. Complicated is not always fundable, and it is certainly not what constituents see in a headline. A wall is simple."
    hide dr_elara_voss
    show aiden_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    aiden_reyes "Simple doesn't mean right. Do you want a picture for a paper or a town that lasts beyond your term?"
    "The exchange snaps like a tightened line. People lean forward. The pier becomes electric—the kind of energy that can be coaxed toward work or split into arguments."
    "You feel the band of determination in your chest tighten. This is what your plan was always meant to be: messy, collaborative, at risk of unraveling if pulled too hard. Negotiation, you think, is knot-tying—pull too hard and it frays. But if you weave the right turns, it holds."
    hide priya_anand
    show maya_kwon at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_kwon "We can make the messaging clear: 'Hybrid protection—community-led, technically reviewed.' We offer inspection schedules, anchor specs, and a timeline for when the low-profile defenses are considered. We can give the council the headlines they need—and the real protections we want."

    councilor_tomas_hale "Headlines that read 'Town Protected'—that I can sell. But the electorate wants to know their boats and businesses are safe tomorrow. How do you prove that, not just promise it?"

    menu:
        "Hand Hale the maintenance rota and meet their eyes":
            "You press the rota into his hands. The paper trembles slightly in your fingers; in his. He reads the numbers and the named signatories. His smile flickers with something like concession."
        "Deflect with a direct question about insurance benchmarks":
            "You ask what insurers need to see. He answers with a list of benchmarks, which Priya immediately begins translating into the grant's conditions. The puzzle pieces click in your mind."

    # --- merge ---
    "The pier hums with decisions being negotiated in real time."
    "The pier hums with decisions being negotiated in real time. Priya taps furiously on her phone, already sketching a conditional grant structure. Aiden haggles with a small group of fishers over platform dimensions. Mateo tells one"
    "more story about a salvage day, and someone adds that tale to the rota—'Community salvage, 1978'—and it becomes a living clause."
    "Dr. Elara Voss, to your surprise, closes her tablet and joins the huddle, pointer finger sketching angles in the air."
    hide councilor_tomas_hale
    show dr_elara_voss at center:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_elara_voss "We model a conservative anchor load factor and we double-schedule post-storm inspections for the first two years. If the model deviates by more than five percent after a major event, our agreement triggers a reassessment. That protects insurers and prioritizes ecology."
    "A burst of applause—small, immediate—ripples through the group. Some fishers exchange looks that mean 'maybe' and others that mean 'finally.'"
    "You feel buoyed by it: the mix of technical discipline and neighborhood stubbornness is exactly what this town needs. Your patience—tightened into resolve—becomes a steady pulse. The co-op's compromise might hold, but it will require constant"
    "vigilance. You can taste the possibility, metallic and bright, the way it makes your mouth water for work."
    hide aiden_reyes
    hide maya_kwon
    hide dr_elara_voss

    scene bg ch7_453e40_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The tide whispers beneath the pier; people's footsteps on wet wood]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Climactic chord building, then easing into a hopeful motif]
    "You close your notebook for a second, feeling the leather and the familiar dent where a pen has marked too many late nights. Around you, the town's patchwork resolve is knitting into something more than a meeting: a plan with names, numbers, and teeth."
    show maya_kwon at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_kwon "This is how we keep the marsh breathing and the boats out at dawn."
    "Page-turn thought: The plan is not finished. It will be argued over paper and at council tables and in storms, but tonight the town has chosen a path through the knotted tide. You tuck your notebook"
    "under your arm, feeling the hum of people ready to work, and walk toward the channel where the pilot eelgrass beds catch the last light."
    hide maya_kwon

    scene bg ch7_453e40_5 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A soft cheer from the pier, then the distant rattle of tools being packed away]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Fade to a single, warm piano note]
    "You know the next meeting is already drawing near—the council, the funders, the engineers. You have to translate tonight's momentum into precise language and louder allies. You breathe in the salt and the plan and feel the rush of momentum under your ribs."

    scene bg ch7_453e40_6 at full_bg
